  "texts": [
    "Davidson shares this intuition.",
    "However, since he wants to give an account of human action that respects what he sees as the requirement that all teleological order in action be derived from internal processes, he cannot adopt the Anscombean solution to the worry.",
    "This is to appeal to practically rational norms in evaluating what it is for the whole causal pathway across both the internal and the external components of the action and its consequences.",
    "In the terms introduced above, the path from the climber's psychological state through to the ensuing events does not express the right kind of teleological microstructure.",
    "This is because what Anscombe would see as the putatively rationally structured transition from the climber's apprehension of the situation to what he does is mediated by something non-rational (a jolt of horror) and is therefore not an expression of intention."
  ],
